# Toronto Rising — development style

This project is iterated **quickly**; requirements and layout change often.

## Prefer a minimal, current codebase

- **Do not** keep unused functions, dead branches, “just in case” placeholders, or obsolete compatibility shims unless the user explicitly asks to preserve them.
- **Do not** assume backward compatibility is required. When something is replaced or no longer referenced, **remove** it and update docs/comments that still describe the old behavior.
- When touching an area, **delete** clearly orphaned code paths rather than leaving commented-out or parallel “legacy” copies.
- After removals, **grep** for stale names (roles, tags, helpers) and fix **call sites, prints, and `.dev` docs** that still mention them.

## Documentation
When behavior, paths, or APIs change, **update `.dev/` and `docs/solutions/` in the same change** — do not wait for the user to ask. Start from [`AGENTS.md`](../../AGENTS.md) and [`.dev/DOCS_INDEX.md`](../../.dev/DOCS_INDEX.md) to find the relevant docs.

## Linear Tracking
Keep Linear, [RUNNING TASKLIST](../../.dev/RUNNING%20TASKLIST.md), and code aligned on every task — see `.cursor/rules/toronto-rising-linear.mdc`. Linear sync is part of done, not a follow-up. Quick capture before scheduling: [INBOX.md](../../.dev/INBOX.md).

## Synchronization Flow & Naming Conventions
For synchronization flow and naming conventions, follow `.cursor/rules/toronto-rising-synchronization.mdc`.

## TTS API heavy-workload guardrails
Before merging Lua/XML changes that touch TTS APIs, read [TTS API Heavy-Workload Catalog](../../.dev/Sychronizing%20Game%20Functionality/TTS-API-Heavy-Workload-Catalog.md), [TTS API Heavy-Workload Usage Inventory](../../.dev/Sychronizing%20Game%20Functionality/TTS-API-Heavy-Workload-Usage-Inventory.md), [Performance Audit](../../.dev/Sychronizing%20Game%20Functionality/Performance%20Audit.md), and [Event Listener Policy](../../.dev/Sychronizing%20Game%20Functionality/Event%20Listener%20Policy.md). In hot callbacks, timers, repeated reconcilers, scene/table/seat/location apply paths, UI fan-out, and object scan/spawn/component-update paths, require a cheap guard or skip condition before expensive work: GUID/object identity, seat/color/tag bound, cached index, fingerprint/dirty check, narrower sync delta, chunk/defer plan, or explicit cold/setup/debug-only note. Do not duplicate broad `StorytellerScenesPanel.refresh`, `UpdateUIDisplays`, full HUD, top-fog, CSHEET, or other broad refreshes immediately after `Sync.full`, `Sync.player`, or a domain reconciler without documenting the missing delta.

## Multiplayer Authority
- **Multiplayer authority:** Initial multiclient E2E (**TOR-144** / **TOR-249**) **passed** (2026-07-13). Still uphold **P1–P10** on every feature touching events, load, HUD, or world I/O — see [`.cursor/rules/toronto-rising-multiplayer-authority.mdc`](../../.cursor/rules/toronto-rising-multiplayer-authority.mdc) and [Preparing For Multiplayer](../../.dev/Multiplayer%20Functionality/Preparing%20For%20Multiplayer.md) §1. Solo Host remains insufficient for join-client-only quirks; residual missing join HUD is **TOR-381** (TTS External). Update [Event Listener Policy](../../.dev/Sychronizing%20Game%20Functionality/Event%20Listener%20Policy.md) when adding handlers.
- **Lua local function order (top recurring runtime bug):** In each file/chunk, define `local function` helpers **before** any caller (`Global.*`, `HUD_*`, `onObject*`, other locals), or forward-declare (`local foo` at top, `foo = function` later). Late locals are invisible to earlier functions → **`attempt to call a nil value`**; build does not catch it. **Before finishing any Lua task:** grep new helper names vs caller line numbers. See [`.cursor/rules/toronto-rising-lua-local-function-order.mdc`](../../.cursor/rules/toronto-rising-lua-local-function-order.mdc) and [`docs/solutions/lua-local-function-order.md`](../../docs/solutions/lua-local-function-order.md). **Do not append new `local function` at file bottom** without checking all callers above.
- **Object script `require()` / bundling (Save & Play payload):** Object-hosted scripts (`objects/*`, CSHEET, dice bags, candles, …) are bundled **per object**. **Never** pull `core.*`, `lib.constants`, or other wide libraries — import **piecemeal** thin object-only modules or use **`Global.call`**. One bad require × 22 dice bags can break Save & Play. See [`.cursor/rules/toronto-rising-object-script-bundling.mdc`](../../.cursor/rules/toronto-rising-object-script-bundling.mdc).
- Give proactive pushback when a requested path is unsound or overly complex; explain the risk and propose a simpler architecture-aligned alternative immediately.
- Favor single-authority ownership per subsystem and call out dual-writer/dual-source-of-truth designs before implementing them.
- **Author session facts:** Do not speculate about what the author may or may not have done (Save & Play, manual clicks, save GUIDs, test re-arm). Ask them to confirm. See [`.cursor/rules/toronto-rising-author-session.mdc`](../../.cursor/rules/toronto-rising-author-session.mdc).
- **Aggressive committing in Cursor:** Commit after each logical unit without asking unless the active user request explicitly says not to. See [`.cursor/rules/toronto-rising-git.mdc`](../../.cursor/rules/toronto-rising-git.mdc).
